{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2012}} On 25 May 2005 to 3 August 2005, [[Moscow]]'s ten-week-long in was a power supplies were the centre of a major incident, restored 3 August 2005, which resulted in the supply being outed for several hours in many of City of Moscow districts, as well as [[Moscow Oblast|Moscow]], [[Tula Oblast|Tula]], [[Kaluga Oblast|Kaluga]] and [[Ryazan Oblast|Ryazan]] provinces. Some tens of thousands of people were trapped in stranded underground trains in the [[Moscow Metro]] and in [[elevator]]s, railway signaling was put out of action and many commercial and governmental organisations were paralysed.<ref name="urlMoscow hit by power blackout - : news, world | euronews">{{cite web |url=http://www.euronews.net/2005/05/25/moscow-hit-by-power-blackout/ |title=Moscow hit by power blackout - : news, world &#124; euronews |format= |work= |accessdate=19 October 2009}}</ref><ref name="urlChubais’ post and career on line for Moscow power failure | The Russia Journal">{{cite web |url=http://www.russiajournal.com/node/19541 |title=Chubais’ post and career on line for Moscow power failure &#124; The Russia Journal |format= |work= |accessdate=19 October 2009}}</ref><ref name="urlXinhua - English">{{cite web |url=http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2005-05/25/content_3002837.htm |title=Xinhua - English |work= |accessdate=19 October 2009}}</ref>
== Occurrence == [[Image:2005 Moscow powerless trolleybus.jpg|thumb|right|The blackout day, Warshawskoe avenue, Moscow. People are heading home by foot. Note that the faces/billboards are covered by the photographer for security reasons.]] The accident, which some accounts state affected more than 2 [[million]] people, started in powerstation no. 510 Chagino, situated in the south-east of Moscow in the Kuzminki district. Here, the high voltage (500 kV) current, going into the capital along the main power lines, is lowered via transformers for city usage to 220 kV and 110 kV.
The Chagino substation, built in 1964, is equipped with six high-to-low transformers. Another six substations situated around the [[MKAD]] carry out the same functions, and form the Moscow energy ring, which supply Moscow and neighbouring provinces with electricity.{{citation needed|date=February 2015}}
== Theories of cause == The immediate cause of the incident, some state, was a mixture of several factors, among which feature: equipment wear-and-tear, absence of back-up powers, the fact that Moscow had endured temperatures above 30&nbsp;°C for a number of days. Moreover, Moscow is a very complex region and has the most complex electrical schemata, or "copper board", as it is known by those in the business. It is the only region in which there has been no automatic shut-off system installed since the fall of the [[Soviet Union]]. This increased vulnerability of Moscow's electrical network played an important role in what happened.
