{{Infobox rail accident | title = Arzamas explosion / Arzamas train disaster | date = 4 June 1988 | time = 9:32 | image = |caption = | location = Arzamas-1 station | location-city = [[Arzamas]], [[Nizhny Novgorod Oblast|Gorky Oblast]] | country = [[Soviet Union]] | line = | operator = | type = Explosion | cause = | trains = | deaths = 91 | injuries = 1,500 }}
The '''Arzamas explosion''', also known as the '''Arzamas train disaster''', was a [[railway accident]] that occurred on June 4, 1988 in [[Arzamas]], [[Nizhny Novgorod Oblast|Gorky Oblast]], [[Soviet Union]], when an [[explosion]] at a [[railway crossing]] killed 91 people and injured 1,500.<ref name=nyt-explo>{{cite news |last1=Taubman |first1=Philip |title=Soviet Freight Train Explodes, Killing at Least 68 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1988/06/06/world/soviet-freight-train-explodes-killing-at-least-68.html |accessdate=August 18, 2015 |work=New York Times |date=June 6, 1988}}</ref>
A [[freight train]] featuring three [[goods wagon]]s carrying 118 tons of [[explosives]] from [[Dzerzhinsk, Russia|Dzerzhinsk]] to the [[Kazakh Soviet Socialist Republic|Kazakh SSR]] exploded at a railway crossing near the [[Arzamas I railway station|Arzamas-1]] train station when [[hexogen]] included in the load detonated for unknown reasons, also detonating the other explosives stored in the wagons. The explosion also caused major damage to Arzamas, creating a 26&nbsp;metre deep crater (85&nbsp;ft), destroying 151 buildings including 2 hospitals, 49 [[kindergartens]], 14 schools, 69 stores, and around 823 families were left homeless. It destroyed 250 meters of railroad tracks, an [[electrical substation]], some [[power lines]], and damaged the [[gas pipeline]] and the railway station.
The officially accepted cause of the explosion is considered to be violation of the rules of loading and transportation of explosives. Alternative theories by some, including Nizhny Novgorod Oblast governor Gennady Khodyrev, have believed the explosion was planned as a [[terrorist]] act or as the actions of foreign [[special forces|special services]] with the purpose of forcing instability in the Soviet Union. The Arzamas train disaster occurred exactly a year before the [[Ufa train disaster]], one of the deadliest railway accidents in Soviet and Russian history.
