{{Infobox recurring event | name = Jersey International Air Display | image = Jersey air display spectators in 2012.JPG | caption = Crowds watch the display in 2012. | status = <!-- e.g. defunct, active, inactive ... --> | genre = [[military]] and civilian [[air show]] | dates = September | frequency = Annually | venue = [[Jersey Airport]] | location = Jersey, Channel Islands | coordinates = | country = [[Jersey]] | established = 1952<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.societe-jersiaise.org/photographic-archive/|title=Photo with reference SJPA/034015 dated 1953 and the 2nd event|website=Societe-jersiaise.org|accessdate=2016-04-21}}</ref> | attendance = | activity = | organised = | website = {{URL|http://www.jerseyairdisplay.org.uk/}} }}
The '''Jersey International Air Display''' is an [[air show]] which is held every year on the island of Jersey, in the [[Channel Islands]]. It normally consists of one air display and two static displays - one at the airport and one in a park in St. Helier.
It is a non-profit making event, and relies upon sponsorship and government funding.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/europe/3201929.stm|title=BBC NEWS - Europe - Air display under threat|website=News.bbc.co.uk|accessdate=2016-04-21}}</ref> The main display can be watched by the public, free of charge.
Some of the aircraft carry out displays over [[Guernsey]], as part of the [[Guernsey Air Display]] (formerly the Guernsey Battle of Britain Air Display), on the same day.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.guernseyairdisplay.co.uk/introduction.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=April 1, 2012 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120611012645/http://www.guernseyairdisplay.co.uk/introduction.htm |archivedate=June 11, 2012 }}</ref>
==Performers== [[File:Red Arrows in formation.JPG|thumb|right|The Red Arrows performing during the 2009 show.]] Regular performers include the [[Red Arrows]], [[RAF Falcons]] [[parachute]] display team, and the [[Battle of Britain Memorial Flight]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jerseyairdisplay.org.uk/links.shtml|title=Jersey International Air Display - Links|author=Darren Dupre|website=Jerseyairdisplay.org.uk|accessdate=2016-04-21}}</ref>
Notable appearances include; {{columns-list|colwidth=30em| *[[Avro Lancaster]] (BBMF) *[[Avro Vulcan]] *[[Boeing B-17 Flying Fortress|B-17 Flying Fortress]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/local/jersey/hi/people_and_places/nature/newsid_8248000/8248246.stm|title=BBC - Jersey - What's on at the Air Display '09|website=News.bbc.co.uk|accessdate=2016-04-21}}</ref> *[[Boeing B-52 Stratofortress|B-52 Stratofortress]] *[[Belgian Air Component|BAF]] [[General Dynamics F-16 Fighting Falcon|F-16 Fighting Falcon]] *[[Eurofighter Typhoon]] *[[Grumman TBF Avenger]] *[[Hawker Hurricane]] (BBMF) *Hawker Siddeley Harrier *[[North American B-25 Mitchell]] *[[Supermarine Spitfire|Spitfire]] (BBMF)<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/local/jersey/hi/front_page/newsid_8246000/8246027.stm|title=BBC - Jersey - Flying a Battle of Britain legend|website=News.bbc.co.uk|accessdate=2016-04-21}}</ref> *[[Panavia Tornado|Tornado GR4]] *[[Westland Dragonfly]] *[[Yves Rossy]] (Jetman) *[[BAe Nimrod]] - The last ever display appearance of the Nimrod MRA4 took place at the Jersey Airshow in 2010 *[[Saab Viggen]] - First ever UK appearance of the Swedish Historic Flight Viggen *[[Saab Tunnan]] *[[Saab 105]] *[[Saab Lansen]] }}
==History== [[File:HMS Ocean off St Helier Jersey.JPG|thumb|right|HMS Ocean anchored off [[Saint Helier|St. Helier]] during the 2009 show.]] In 1997, [[Mike Higgins (Jersey politician)|Mike Higgins]] became the display organiser.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jerseyairdisplay.org.uk/whoswho.shtml|title=Jersey International Air Display - Who's Who|author=Darren Dupre|website=Jerseyairdisplay.org.uk|accessdate=2016-04-21|publisher=}}</ref>
In 2009, [[HMS Ocean (L12)]] was present, and participated in the event.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/europe/jersey/8246471.stm|title=BBC NEWS - Europe - Jersey - Island prepares for air display|website=News.bbc.co.uk|accessdate=2016-04-21}}</ref>
The 2011 air display was canceled, due to poor visibility, shortly before it was due to start.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-jersey-14843267|title=Jersey air display is cancelled due to bad weather|website=Bbc.co.uk|accessdate=2016-04-21}}</ref> Most aircraft which were due to take part had already arrived on the island.
==Accidents and incidents related to air show== * September 1991: The Hawker Hurricane IIC LF363 suffered an engine failure en route to Jersey and crash landed at [[RAF Wittering]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.raf.mod.uk/bbmf/history/historyofflight.cfm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=May 30, 2010 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100330031616/http://www.raf.mod.uk/bbmf/history/historyofflight.cfm |archivedate=March 30, 2010 }}</ref> * 6 September 2006: A privately owned [[Lockheed T-33 Shooting Star|T-33]] crashed on take-off close to the [[Imperial War Museum Duxford]], on its way to the Jersey show.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/cambridgeshire/5320788.stm|title=BBC NEWS - UK - England - Cambridgeshire - Aircraft crash at historic museum|website=News.bbc.co.uk|accessdate=2016-04-21}}</ref> * 10 September 2003: A [[Hawker Siddeley Harrier|Harrier]] jet experienced hydraulic problems shortly before landing at Jersey Airport.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/europe/3097912.stm|title=BBC NEWS - Europe - Harrier in emergency alert|website=News.bbc.co.uk|accessdate=2016-04-21}}</ref> * 9 September 2003: A [[BAE Systems Hawk|Hawk]] overshot the runway while landing at Jersey Airport in advance of an air display. Minor damage was caused to the aircraft.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/world/europe/3093782.stm|title=BBC NEWS - Europe - Red Arrows jet in runway drama|website=News.bbc.co.uk|accessdate=2016-04-21}}</ref>
